
# Operating Model — Deferred Items and TODOs

Items accumulated from Definition Model and Work Model discussions that are explicitly scoped for the Operating Model. Organized by facet (Coordination, Organization) and by source concern.

---

## 1. Internal Structure and Naming

The Operating Model's internal structure (subdivision terminology, entity catalog) is deliberately unnamed. "Coordination" and "Organization" are working labels, not architectural terms. The naming will emerge through modeling work, as it did for the Definition Model (9 Dimensions) and Work Model (5 Tracks).

    ☐ Determine the Operating Model's internal subdivision pattern
    ☐ Decide if a third facet exists beyond Coordination and Organization
    ☐ Earn the structural metaphor through iterative modeling (don't prematurely name)

See: DR-014, README.md (Operating Model section), FAQ Q28

---

## 2. Coordination Facet:

### 2.1 Ceremonies and Cadences:

    ☐ Define ceremonies for each Work Model track:
        ☐ Discovery Track: Signal Review, Prioritization Review, Deliberation scheduling, Initiative Review
        ☐ Build Track: Sprint Planning, Release Planning ceremonies, Architecture Review Board
        ☐ Run Track: Deployment review, Incident review, Change Advisory Board
        ☐ Win Track: QBR cadence, Pipeline review, Win/Loss review scheduling, Engagement prioritization
        ☐ Evolve Track: Evolution cycle kick-off, Evolve Review scheduling, Definition review ceremonies
    ☐ Define cross-track coordination ceremonies (e.g., Customer Release readiness review spanning Build/Run/Win)
    ☐ Define decision-making rhythms — who decides what, at what cadence, with what authority

### 2.2 Planning Cadences:

    ☐ Define planning cadence for each track (the Work Model defines planning entities but not when/how often they run)
    ☐ Address Win Track's continuous flow (kanban) — planning is periodic but work item size is independent of planning cadence
    ☐ Address Evolve Track's periodic review cycles — typically quarterly or aligned to organizational change events

